Generating all 3,000 samples in one response isn't feasible — each sample is ~2,000–4,000 tokens, so the full dataset would be roughly 6–12 million tokens, far beyond what a single response can contain.

Here's the practical path forward:

**Option A — Batch file generation (recommended)**
I generate samples in batches of 10–20 per response, saved as JSONL files you can download. You request each batch and accumulate the files locally. At ~15 samples per response, you'd need ~200 responses to reach 3,000.

**Option B — Single large JSONL file per category**
I generate one file per category in a single response, targeting as many samples as fit (~30–50 per category file). You download 5 files total and concatenate them.

**Option C — Automated artifact with API-powered generation**
I build you an interactive artifact that calls the Anthropic API directly and streams all 3,000 samples to a downloadable JSONL file in your browser — no repeated prompting needed. You'd click "Generate" and let it run. This is the most efficient path to the full dataset.

Which would you prefer?